Itis characteristic of Horace that in the very next Satire he makes his own servant Davus tell him that his rhapso- dies about the country and its charms are mere humbug, and that, for all his ridicule of the shortcomings of his neighbours‚ he is just as inconstant as they are in his likings and dislikings. The poet in this way lets us see into his own little vanities, and secures the right by doing so to rally his friends for theirs. To his valet, at all eventS, by his own showing, he is no hero.
